    "texts": [
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Previous names",
            "shortText": "<p><i>Asterias fragilis</i></p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_9_1855",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Identification features",
            "shortText": "<p>Disc more of less pentagonal, dorsal surface covered in spines, smaller spinelets and stumps (often intermixed, but separately in <i>var. triglochis</i>), radial shields large and triangular, may be naked but covered in stumps (only in var. <i>triglochis)</i>. Arms relatively short and fringed with long spines that project at right-angles and become progressively shorter towards tips of arms.</p><p>Colour extremely variable and often strikingly attractive. Common colours include combinations of greens, browns, purples, pinks, oranges and reds. The arms are often banded, have a central band of bright colour, or rows of dorsal spots.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_1_1856",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Adult size",
            "shortText": "<p>Arm length up to 50 mm.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_2_1857",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Distribution",
            "shortText": "<p><u>Global:</u> Widespread in European waters, Mediterranean, North Sea, North-East Atlantic, down the west coast of Africa and around South Africa.</p><p><u>Local/Regional:</u> Namibia to Kosi Bay.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_3_1858",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Biology",
            "shortText": "<p>Common from the intertidal to depths of about 350 m. Coastal specimens usually concealed under rocks,in kelp holdfasts, in gravel or other cryptic habitats. In deeper water may form large aggregations on reefs or soft substrata, all holding their arms up into the water current to intercept passing detritus.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_4_1859",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Food / prey",
            "shortText": "<p>Solitary individuals normally act as scavengers picking up detrital particles on the sediment surface. In deeper waters the arms are held up into the water column to intercept passing particles in the water column. In most detritus feeding brittle stars the tube feet grasp prey items and compact them into balls, which are then transported along cilial tract on the underside of the arms to the central mouth, but this species is also reported to pass the food to the mouth by curling the arms.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_5_1860",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Reproduction",
            "shortText": "<p>In Europe spawn once a year, the fertilized eggs developing into planktonic larvae that take about 3 weeks to develop before settling onto suitable habitats. Newly settled juveniles have a disc diameter of just 2 mm and only 2 segments per arm.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_6_1861",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Similar species",
            "shortText": "<p>The most common of several local species in this diverse genus. Differ from most other regional brittle stars by having very spinose dorsal surface to the disc. Most of the other regional species occur in the warmer waters of the east coast, but <i>O. aristulata</i> is also common in the Western Cape, although usually in deeper waters than <i>O. fragilis</i>.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_7_1862",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Further reading / References",
            "shortText": "Branch, G, Griffiths, CL, Branch, M & Beckley, L (2022). Two Oceans: A Guide to the Marine Life of Southern Africa. (Fifth edition) Struik Nature, Cape Town. (p. 230).<br><br>Clark, AM & Courtman-Stock, J (1976). The Echinoderms of Southern Africa. British Museum (Natural History), London (p. 144).<br><br>Olbers, JM, Griffiths, CL, O'Hara, TD & Samyn, Y (2019). Field guide to the brittle and basket stars (Echinodermata: Ophiuroidea) of South Africa. <i>ABC Taxa</i>, 19, 1–346 (p. 284).",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_8_1863",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        }
    ],
